Regridding of Globcolour dataset

Teresa Martin

Data cleaning and manipulation

Map projections

As discussed in Section XXX, The NSIDC data is in a polar stereographic projection. This avoids the distortion at the poles which is common in equirectangular projections [REF]. As this projection is the most appropriate one for investigating the Arctic region, all other datasets used for the investigation use the same projection.
Conversely, the globcolour data is in a standard PC equirectangular projection (ESRIXXXX). Consequently, it must be cropped and reshaped appropriately to fit the data from NSIDC.

Data retrieval

The first step is to retrieve the data, from both the NSIDC and from the Globcolour project. The function wget was used to establish the directory listing of data from the globcolour file-transfer protocol (FTP) site. The open-source FTP software FileZilla was then used to recursively retrieve all of the relevant files using wild-cards, and collapsing the folder structure to place all of the data in one folder [REF TO FILEZILLA WEBSITE].
Similarly to the Globcolour data, wget and FileZilla were used to locate and retrieve relevant information last retreat day. Information on last retreat days is publicly available via the NSIDC FTP site.

############################ Data download ############################
# IMPORTANT - the globcolour server counts transition from pasive to active connection as a re-connection

#Drop everything to clear memory
#rm(list=ls())
# STORY: If the length of a vector of the elements which are in packs
# but not in installed.packages() is greater than 0, install the
# packages with the values of that vector, otherwise print a message
# saying that all the packages you've specified are already installed
loader <- function(packs) {
  system.time(
    if (length(setdiff(packs, rownames(installed.packages()))) > 0) {
      print("you need the following packages to run this script")
      print(setdiff(packs, rownames(installed.packages())))
      print("Installing them now...")
      install.packages(setdiff(packs, rownames(installed.packages())))
      print("Now loading libraries...")
      sapply(packs, require, character.only = TRUE)
    } else {
      print("All packages are installed already")
      print("Loading the specified libraries...")
      sapply(packs, require, character.only = TRUE)
    }
  )
}

# NB rproj files enforce relative folder addresses
print_folder <- function(folder) {
  if (folder == "output") {
  paste0(base_folder_abs, output_folder_str)
  } else if (folder == "glob") {
  paste0(base_folder_abs_1up, glob_folder_str)
  } else if (folder == "ice") {
  paste0(base_folder_abs_1up, ice_folder_str)  
  }else if (folder == "base") {
  print(base_folder_abs)
  } else {
  print("please use: glob, ice, base or output")
  stop()
  }
}

Now we have all the materials we need to use GDAL to re-project the data.

Regridding process using GDAL

The geospatial data abstraction library (GDAL) is an open-source set of tools for manipulating geospatial data http://www.gdal.org/. The GIS software QGIS, and the programming language R both include user-friendly methods for interracting with GDAL in order to manipulate gridded datasets, and also conveniently for translating filetypes. These resources were used here to manipulate the original GlobColour dataset into the NSIDC polar-stereographic north projection, restricted to the same extents.

The regridding process in this case was broken up into the following 3 steps:

  1. Translate the netCDF (.nc) file from Globcolour into a GeoTiff (a file type which is compatible with almost all GIS sofwares), and Only extract the mean chlorophyll-\(\alpha\) variable (called CHL1_mean)
  2. Re-project the resulting GeoTiff in an EPSG:4326 (equirectangular) grid, only taking data above 30\(^{\circ}\) north in latitude (thus matching the extent of the NSIDC data)
  3. Re-project the resulting GeoTiff to a EPSG:3411 (NSIDC polar-stereographic) projection, using the command gdalwarp

This was repeated for each of the 695 .nc files. GDAL must be version 2+, or the algorithm will be incorrect. The below demonstrates this process for a single file. Figure XXX shows the results in a basic form

# make sure we're still in base to start
print_folder("base")
[1] "D:/UCL/Dissertation/CODE"
# for each GLOBFILE:
  # move file into CODE folder for processing
  # Translate .nc file to geotiff & delete original
  # Reproject to EPSG:4326 at lat 30deg+ north & delete one before
  # reproject to EPSG:3411 & delete one before
  # move the final file into the OUTPUT folder
#example with 1 file. Lay out all of the strings we need for automatic renaming
glob_original_filename <- glob_filenames[1]
glob_variable_filename <- glob_filenames2[1]
#Create function to regrid 4326 to a 3411 (NSIDC's northern hemisphere ps)
regrid_4326_to_3411N <-
  function(orig_filename,orig_filename_with_variable) {
  
  glob_converted_filename <- 
    gsub(pattern = ".nc",replacement = "_mean.tif",glob_original_filename)
  glob_reproj_filename <-
    gsub(pattern = ".tif",replacement = "_wgs84.tif",x = glob_converted_filename)
  glob_warped_filename <-
    gsub(pattern = "_wgs84.tif",replacement = "_ps.tif",glob_reproj_filename)
  glob_original_location <-
    paste0(print_folder("glob"), glob_original_filename)
  
  #print for debugging
  # glob_original_filename
  # glob_variable_filename
  # glob_converted_filename
  # glob_reproj_filename
  # glob_warped_filename
  # glob_original_location
  
  #copy the file from the data folder for globcolour
  if (file.exists(glob_original_location) == FALSE) {
  print("the file does not exist")
  stop()
  } else {
  file.copy(from = glob_original_location, to = print_folder("base"))
  }
  # If the file exists in the working directory:
  # convert to geoTIFF
  if (file.exists(glob_original_filename) == FALSE) {
  print("The file didn't copy properly")
  stop()
  } else {
  gdal_translate(src_dataset = glob_variable_filename,
  of = "GTiff",
  dst_dataset = glob_converted_filename)
  }
  #remove the origingal file to save space on disk:
  file.remove(glob_original_filename)
  #reproject to EPSG:4326 to make sure it's aligned in the GeoTiff format
  gdal_translate(
  a_srs = "EPSG:4326",
  projwin = c(-180, 90, 180, 30),
  src_dataset = glob_converted_filename,
  dst_dataset = glob_reproj_filename
  )
  #remove the converted but not reprojected one to save space on disk:
  file.remove(glob_converted_filename)
  
  # warp the reprojected map onto a polar sterographic EPSG:3411 grid
  # match the target extent (in metres)
  # Code Sourced from Terry Haran at NSIDC 
  gdalwarp(
  t_srs = "EPSG:3411",
  ts = c(304, 448),
  te = c(-3850000.000, -5350000.000, 3750000.000, 5850000.000),
  wo = list("SAMPLE_GRID=YES", "SAMPLE_STEPS=300", "SOURCE_EXTRA=1000"),
  overwrite = TRUE,
  srcfile = glob_reproj_filename,
  dstfile = glob_warped_filename
  )
  #remove the snipped and aligned to save space on disk:
  file.remove(glob_reproj_filename)
  file.rename(glob_warped_filename,paste0(print_folder("output"),glob_warped_filename))
  }
regrid_4326_to_3411N(orig_filename = glob_filenames[1],
                     orig_filename_with_variable = glob_filenames2[1])
[1] "D:/UCL/Dissertation/CODE"
[1] TRUE
                     
# load in as raster to check integrity (hard-coded)
plot(raster("./OUTPUT/L3m_20020501-20020508__GLOB_25_GSM-MERSWF_CHL1_8D_00_mean_ps.tif"),main="GlobColour image, 1st of May 2002, regridded to NSIDC Polar Stereographic North")

Reorganisation of the data to a long format

When each individual pixel has many observations, and these observations are likely to be correlated with eachother over time, the data is analagous to longitudinal data. Arrangement of data in this format can lead to potentially informative data analysis, including regressions which can capture the association between ice retreat and phytoplankton bloom, whilst also adjusting for confounding factors like regional level characteristics. In this study, the data was treated as such.
The synchronicity between ice melt and subsequent pytoplanktonic bloom requires some measure of time relative to the last-retreat day (LRD), or last day before the sea ice concentration (SIC) in a region (pixel) falls below a given threshold. However, as previously discussed, this association could be confounded by the amount of available solar radiation at LRD, following LRD, or increasingly possibly before LRD with continually thinning ice in the Arctic. In order to conduct this analysis, the following workflow was used for each of the 1.3619210^{5} pixels, for each year between 2002 and 2008, for every 8-day extent covered, for each of the four SIC thresholds:

  1. Reformulate the dataset to be longitudinal in shape, to allow appropriate data analysis
  2. calculate Julian day (JD) corresponding to LRD, adjusting for leap years
  3. for each year, remove those pixels with no LRD, as there is no basis on which to examine syncronicity
  4. Calculate day length each GlobColour chl-a image, using latitude of pixel, longitude of pixel, and the insol R-package
  5. calculate JDs since LRD and chl-a level for all pixels with an LRD
  6. Estimate the difference in time between LRD and chl-a measurement in daylight hours

This workflow allows an unadjusted and adjusted analysis to be conducted, to show the importance of adjusting for levels of solar radiation. The result is a 2-d array which is identifyable by pixel on the image (they are numbered 1-1.3619210^{5}), by point in time, and by SIC threshold. This data structure is ideal for time-series or longitudinal data analysis. This approach also allowed time-invariant unobservable heterogeneity between regions to be taken into account, leading to a statistical analysis which was robust to year-round differences in temperature, nutrient levels, salinity, ocean depth and any other constant factors which may affect phytoplankton bloom syncronicity with light availability.

Applying a regional mask

A regional analysis may be informative, as different regions may follow different annual patterns of ice retreat and ice advance, which may over time lead to a difference in species distribution or other factors which could affect the syncronicity between ice retreat and phytoplankton bloom. For this reason, a regional mask was applied. This mask was supplied by Prof. Stroeve, defining the major regions in the Arctic. The below table shows the values of the regional mask:

Number region
0 non-ocean water
1 Other
2 Sea of Okhotsk
3 Bearing sea
4 Hudson
5 St. Lawrence
6 Baffin Bay
7 East Greenland
8 Barents
9 Kara
10 Laptev sea
11 East siberian sea
12 Chuckchi
13 Beaufort
14 CCA
15 Central arctic
20 Land Mask
21 coastline

The regional analysis is focused on Arctic regions, and other regions (including region 0 in the above) are dropped from the dataset.

Calculating Julian day corresponding to LRD

Pixels may retreat at different times when the definition of retreat is changed. A higher SIC threshold may lead to earlier LRD in some cases and none at all in others. This is because an area at a very high SIC has to melt less to count as having retreated at a higher threhold, yet some areas may never reach a high enough concentration to be defined as having ‘advanced’ in the first place in a high threshold. The data covers 4 leap years, and the NSIDC LRD and FAD data starts at March 1st each year to avoid issues of alignment. 59 was be added to LRD and FAD for non-leap-years and 60 was added for leap-years.

the parts of this process are: 1. load in the geotiff of LRD as raster data 2. convert this raster data into a matrix of numerical values 3. add 59 or 60 to all of the values which are not labelled as missing (-99 in dataset)

#create a directory of all file information
#folders
lrd_folder_SIC15 <- "../DATA/LRD/SIC15/"
lrd_folder_SIC30 <- "../DATA/LRD/SIC30/"

#convert matrix to column vector
lrd <- c(lrd)
#repeat as a function
LOAD_LRD_YEAR <- function(SIC_threshold,year) {
  #select the right file address
  if (SIC_threshold == 15) {
    file <- LRD_FILES_REF$SIC15$address[match(year,LRD_FILES_REF$SIC15$year)]
  } else if (SIC_threshold == 30) {
    file <- LRD_FILES_REF$SIC30$address[match(year,LRD_FILES_REF$SIC30$year)]
  } else if (SIC_threshold == 50) {
    file <- LRD_FILES_REF$SIC50$address[match(year,LRD_FILES_REF$SIC50$year)]
  } else if (SIC_threshold == 75) {
    file <- LRD_FILES_REF$SIC75$address[match(year,LRD_FILES_REF$SIC75$year)]
  } else {
    stop("Please select 15, 30, or 50 as SIC threshold")
  }
  lrd <- raster(file)
  #code NAs
  lrd[lrd == -99] <- NA
  #code JD adjustment
  if (any(c(2004,2008,2012,2016)==year)) {
    print("you have selected a leap year, adding 60 to LRD")
    lrd <- lrd + 60
  } else {
    print("you have selected a non-leap year, adding 59 to LRD")
    lrd <- lrd + 59  
  }
  lrd <- c(as.matrix(lrd))
  #make it a dataframe
  lrd <- data.frame(pixel_number=1:(448*304),LRD=lrd,YEAR=year)
  # get rid of pixels with no LRD
  lrd <- lrd[!is.na(lrd$LRD),]
  return(lrd)
}
#example histogram by day
x <- LOAD_LRD_YEAR(SIC_threshold = 15,year = 2002)
[1] "you have selected a non-leap year, adding 59 to LRD"
hist(x$LRD,breaks=365,main="LRD 2002, SIC threshold 15%")

Following this transformation, the resulting data contains NAs for pixels which do not have an LRD for that year, in that SIC threshold, and julian day corresponding to LRD for the rest. the dimensions of the image are 8777872, 23 in rows and columns, respectively.

There are 8777872 pixels from 2002 (out of 8777872) which have a value for LRD.

First advance day

For reference, first advance day was also included in the dataset. This data can be used to remove the pixels from the final analysis which ‘re-freeze’, so that the mean CHL1 is not dragged down by lots of zero values.

#repeat as a function
LOAD_FAD_YEAR <- function(SIC_threshold,year) {
  #select the right file address
  if (SIC_threshold == 15) {
    file <- FAD_FILES_REF$SIC15$address[match(year,FAD_FILES_REF$SIC15$year)]
  } else if (SIC_threshold == 30) {
    file <- FAD_FILES_REF$SIC30$address[match(year,FAD_FILES_REF$SIC30$year)]
  } else if (SIC_threshold == 50) {
    file <- FAD_FILES_REF$SIC50$address[match(year,FAD_FILES_REF$SIC50$year)]
  } else if (SIC_threshold == 75){
    file <- FAD_FILES_REF$SIC75$address[match(year,FAD_FILES_REF$SIC75$year)]
  } else {
    stop("Please select 15, 30, or 50 as SIC threshold")
  }
  fad <- raster(file)
  #code NAs
  fad[fad == -99] <- NA
  #code JD adjustment
  if (any(c(2004,2008,2012,2016)==year)) {
    print("you have selected a leap year, adding 60 to LRD")
    fad <- fad + 60
  } else {
    print("you have selected a non-leap year, adding 59 to LRD")
    fad <- fad + 59  
  }
  fad <- c(as.matrix(fad))
  #make it a dataframe by year
  fad <- data.frame(pixel_number=1:(448*304),FAD=fad,YEAR=year)
  # get rid of pixels with no FAD
  fad <- fad[!is.na(fad$FAD),]
  return(fad)
}
head(LOAD_FAD_YEAR(SIC_threshold = 75,year = 2002))

Clorophyll data

For 2002, the first 8-day CHL1 extent covered the start of May 1st to the end of May 8th. May 1st is JD 121 (2002 was not a leap year). For 2002, any day between JD 60 and JD 121 was lost in terms of chlorophyll data. All other chlorophyll data ran from JD 1 to JD365. For each GlobColour file, the representative JD was the nearest ‘whole day’ between the starting date of the 8-day extent and the ending day. This was calculated by rounding \(JD_{start} +\left ( \frac{JD_{end} - JD_{start}}{2} \right )\) to the nearest whole number.The result of this operation, and merging with the main dataset was a dataframe containing information about a pixel, including its latitude, longitude, julian day, pixel number and chl-\(\alpha\) level in \(mgm^{-3}\).

For every pixel which has an observation for LRD, the length of the solar day could then be calculated using insol, using latitude, longitude and the ‘representative’ JD calculated above. Finally, a large proportion of days during each year are in permanent day or night (polar day or night, as discussed in Section XXX), leading to the insol package generating values of “NaN”. These NaN values were assigned either a value of 0 or 24 dependant on the time of year in which the CHL1 data was collected. undefined daylength pixels were assigned 0 or 24 hours of solar day, with JDs between 90 and 273 being assigned 24 and others 0.

In the 2002-2014 period inclusively, approximately XXX%, XXX%, XXX%, and XXX% of the gridded areas (for 15, 30, 50 and 75 percent thresholds respectively) in the arctic region had a day length of under 24 hours at the LRD. Consequently, it would be incorrect to simply assume that the nubmer or days between melt and bloom are represntative of the duration of opportunity for phytoplankton to propogate. It is likely much more accurate to adjust each pixel for the solar day length at the LRD, and to multiply this by the number of days between LRD and the first signs of phytoplankton bloom. In the central arctic region, the proportion of pixels of data which were collected on days betwen 0 and 24 in daylength was XXX%, illustrating how much more extreme the transition from polar day to polar night is when closer to to the pole.

XXX observations on the pixel level (out of total initial observations XXX, 15% threshold) contain positive CHL1 values whilst also being collected in days before the pixel fell below the SIC threshold of 15%. At a higher SIC threhold (75%), this was XXX out of XXX. As discussed in the background section (Section XXX SECTION ON SOLAR RADIATION PERMIATING THE ICE AND ALLOWING PHYTOPLANKTON GROWTH BEFORE EVEN 100% SIC), light can penetrate thinner ice, and in shallower areas, light availability is elevated through reflectance of solar radiation from the ocean floor. Shallower areas of ocean may also have a higher year-round temperature, have lower salinity and also recieve higher quantities of nutrients. All of these factors could affect the opportunity for phytoplankton growth. Consequently, LRD was used as a point of reference to center the data, rather than as a starting point (as this starting point is somewhat arbitrary in reality). This avoided dropping XXX% of the observations for the 15% threshold (XXX% for the 75% threshold).

#Make a list of all CHL1 filenames, ordered by date:
#folder
chlfolder <- "../CODE/OUTPUT/"
#list all files with ".tif" in the name
chlfiles <- list.files("../CODE/OUTPUT/")[grep(".tif",list.files("../CODE/OUTPUT/"))]
#get rid of the metadata xml files (created when opening in qgis)
chlfiles <- chlfiles[-grep(".aux.xml",chlfiles)]
#create a database of files to refer to throughout
chl1_file_database <-
  data.frame(
  filename = chlfiles,
  address = paste0(chlfolder, chlfiles),
  year = substr(chlfiles,5,8),
  startmonth = substr(chlfiles, 9, 10),
  startday = substr(chlfiles, 11, 12),
  endmonth = substr(chlfiles, 18, 19),
  endday = substr(chlfiles, 20, 21),
  stringsAsFactors = FALSE
  )
#calculate julian day from day month year(%d-%m-%Y) (using pipes for transparrency)
chl1_file_database$DATE_start <-
  paste0(chl1_file_database$startday,
         "-",
         chl1_file_database$startmonth,
         "-",
         chl1_file_database$year) %>%
  as.Date(format = "%d-%m-%Y")
chl1_file_database$JDAY_start <- yday(chl1_file_database$DATE_start) %>% as.numeric()
# calculate end day for each file
chl1_file_database$DATE_end <-
  paste0(chl1_file_database$endday,
         "-",
         chl1_file_database$endmonth,
         "-",
         chl1_file_database$year) %>%
  as.Date(format = "%d-%m-%Y") 
chl1_file_database$JDAY_end <- yday(chl1_file_database$DATE_end) %>% as.numeric()
# for each of these, choose the middle day.
chl1_file_database$JDAY_rep <-
  chl1_file_database$JDAY_start + 
  round((chl1_file_database$JDAY_end - chl1_file_database$JDAY_start) /  2, 0)
#test that each file exists
length(file.exists(chl1_file_database$address)) == nrow(chl1_file_database)
[1] TRUE

In the above, the difference between LRD and JDAY_rep is the number of ice-free days in the area up to the date range covered by the chloryphill data. To save memory, pixels without an LRD for that year are removed. The data extraction and manipulation loop is deactivated via comment here, as it takes a long time to run. It also generates a large amount of output text, so only the output from one example year is included in the knit.

#set up function
GET_CHL1_DATA <- function(year,position,LRD_DATA) {
  julian_days <- chl1_file_database[which(chl1_file_database$year==year),"JDAY_rep"]
  julian_day <- julian_days[position]
  address_list <- chl1_file_database[chl1_file_database$year==year,"address"]
  chl <- raster(address_list[position])
  chl <- c(as.matrix(chl))
  chl <-
    data.frame(
    pixel_number = 1:length(chl),
    CHL = chl,
    JD_rep = julian_day,
    stringsAsFactors = FALSE
    )
  #limit to only those pixels in the respective LRD_DATA
  chl <- chl[which(chl$pixel_number %in% LRD_DATA$pixel_number),]
}

OUTPUT_50 <- read.csv("./OUTPUT/DATASET_SIC50.csv")
OUTPUT_75 <- read.csv("./OUTPUT/DATASET_SIC75.csv")

The result of this operation is a dataframe with rows for 15%, 30%, 50% and 75%, each containing information about a pixel within a particular 8-day extent.

For every pixel which has an observation for LRD, the length of the solar day can be calculated using insol. First the latitude and longitude of each pixel can be loaded into the dataset. Following this, the “representative” julian day of each CHL1 pixel (assumed the middle day of the 8-day extent) can be used to calculate day length at that point in time. Finally, a large proportion of days during each year are in permanent day or night, leading to the insol package generating values of “NaN”. These NaN values can be assigned either a value of 0 or 24 dependant on the time of year in which the CHL1 data was collected.

#merge in lat, long and regional mask for each pixel
OUTPUT_15 <- left_join(OUTPUT_15,lat,by="pixel_number")
OUTPUT_15 <- left_join(OUTPUT_15,lon,by="pixel_number")
OUTPUT_15 <- left_join(OUTPUT_15,regional_mask,by="pixel_number")
OUTPUT_30 <- left_join(OUTPUT_30,lat,by="pixel_number")
OUTPUT_30 <- left_join(OUTPUT_30,lon,by="pixel_number")
OUTPUT_30 <- left_join(OUTPUT_30,regional_mask,by="pixel_number")
OUTPUT_50 <- left_join(OUTPUT_50,lat,by="pixel_number")
OUTPUT_50 <- left_join(OUTPUT_50,lon,by="pixel_number")
OUTPUT_50 <- left_join(OUTPUT_50,regional_mask,by="pixel_number")
OUTPUT_75 <- left_join(OUTPUT_75,lat,by="pixel_number")
OUTPUT_75 <- left_join(OUTPUT_75,lon,by="pixel_number")
OUTPUT_75 <- left_join(OUTPUT_75,regional_mask,by="pixel_number")
#day length at each 8-day CHL1 period (assumed the same for 8 days at a time)
OUTPUT_15$CHL_DAYLENGTH <- insol::daylength(lat = OUTPUT_15$lat, long = OUTPUT_15$lon, jd = OUTPUT_15$JD_rep, 0)[,3]
OUTPUT_30$CHL_DAYLENGTH <- insol::daylength(lat = OUTPUT_30$lat, long = OUTPUT_30$lon, jd = OUTPUT_30$JD_rep, 0)[,3]
OUTPUT_50$CHL_DAYLENGTH <- insol::daylength(lat = OUTPUT_50$lat, long = OUTPUT_50$lon, jd = OUTPUT_50$JD_rep, 0)[,3]
OUTPUT_75$CHL_DAYLENGTH <- insol::daylength(lat = OUTPUT_75$lat, long = OUTPUT_75$lon, jd = OUTPUT_75$JD_rep, 0)[,3]
# there are pixels which generate non-finite values (identified as 'NaNs'). For these pixels, the day length is either 24 or 0,
# depending on the time of year
# Between March and september, the north pole has permanent day, and vice versa for october to end of feb.
# an ifelse() can easily be used to replace these values
# here, 90 and 273 are used as julian day thresholds, irrespective of leap year (as it is unlikely to make a difference)
prop_less_24h_15 <- round((sum(is.nan(OUTPUT_15$CHL_DAYLENGTH)) / nrow(OUTPUT_15))*100,2)
prop_less_24h_30 <- round((sum(is.nan(OUTPUT_30$CHL_DAYLENGTH)) / nrow(OUTPUT_30))*100,2)
prop_less_24h_50 <- round((sum(is.nan(OUTPUT_50$CHL_DAYLENGTH)) / nrow(OUTPUT_50))*100,2)
prop_less_24h_75 <- round((sum(is.nan(OUTPUT_75$CHL_DAYLENGTH)) / nrow(OUTPUT_75))*100,2)
#adjust for 24 hour night or day
OUTPUT_15$CHL_DAYLENGTH <-
  ifelse(
  test = is.nan(OUTPUT_15$CHL_DAYLENGTH),
  yes = ifelse(OUTPUT_15$LRD > 90 & OUTPUT_15$LRD < 273, 24, 0),
  no = OUTPUT_15$CHL_DAYLENGTH
  )
OUTPUT_30$CHL_DAYLENGTH <-
  ifelse(
  test = is.nan(OUTPUT_30$CHL_DAYLENGTH),
  yes = ifelse(OUTPUT_30$LRD > 90 &
  OUTPUT_30$LRD < 273, 24, 0),
  no = OUTPUT_30$CHL_DAYLENGTH
  )
OUTPUT_50$CHL_DAYLENGTH <-
  ifelse(
  test = is.nan(OUTPUT_50$CHL_DAYLENGTH),
  yes = ifelse(OUTPUT_50$LRD > 90 &
  OUTPUT_50$LRD < 273, 24, 0),
  no = OUTPUT_50$CHL_DAYLENGTH
  )
OUTPUT_75$CHL_DAYLENGTH <-
  ifelse(
  test = is.nan(OUTPUT_75$CHL_DAYLENGTH),
  yes = ifelse(OUTPUT_75$LRD > 90 &
  OUTPUT_75$LRD < 273, 24, 0),
  no = OUTPUT_75$CHL_DAYLENGTH
  )
#test that it is extreme for the inner arctic region (SIC threshold does not matter for day length))
# NB not many observations because this part of the arctic does not melt as much.
hist(OUTPUT_75[which(OUTPUT_75$region_number == 15), "CHL_DAYLENGTH"], breaks =
24, col = "#458B74")

#in the inner arctic, day length is much more extreme, as expected.
prop_less_24h_75_CA <-
round((nrow(
OUTPUT_75[which(OUTPUT_75$rname == "Central_arctic"), ] %>% filter(CHL_DAYLENGTH > 0 &
CHL_DAYLENGTH < 24)
) / nrow(
OUTPUT_75 %>% filter(rname == "Central_arctic")
)) * 100, 2)

So, in the 2002-2014 period inclusively, approximately 16.4%, 17.53%, 19.18%, and 23.63% of the gridded areas (for 15, 30, 50 and 75 percent thresholds respectively) in the arctic region had a day length of under 24 hours at the LRD. Consequently, it would be incorrect to simply assume that the nubmer or days between melt and bloom are represntative of the duration of opportunity for phytoplankton to propogate. It is likely much more accurate to adjust each pixel for the solar day length at the LRD, and to multiply this by the number of days between LRD and the first signs of phytoplankton bloom. the proportion of pixels of data which were collected on days betwen 0 and 24 in daylength was 18.79%, illustrating how much more extreme the transition from polar day to polar night is in the central Arctic.

Limiting the dataset to only observations to be included in the analysis

#pixels outside of the LRD FAD range
px_out_of_range_15 <- nrow(OUTPUT_15[which(OUTPUT_15$LRD <= OUTPUT_15$JD_rep & !is.na(OUTPUT_15$CHL)),])

2166074 observations on the pixel level (out of total initial observations 9650804, 15% threshold) contain positive CHL1 values whilst also being collected in days before the pixel fell below the SIC threshold of 15%. This perplexes the argument that phytoplankton does not grow until the ice has completely retreated. As discussed in the background section (Section XXX SECTION ON SOLAR RADIATION PERMIATING THE ICE AND ALLOWING PHYTOPLANKTON GROWTH BEFORE EVEN 100% SIC), light can penetrate thinner ice, and in shallower areas, light is intensified through reflectance of solar radiation from the ocean floor. Shallower areas of ocean may also have a higher year-round temperature, have lower salinity and also recieve higher quantities of nutrients. All of these factors could affect the opportunity for phytoplankton growth. Consequently, the last retreat day is used in this analysis as a point of reference to center the data, rather than as a starting point (as this starting point is somewhat arbitrary in reality). This avoids dropping 22.44% of the observations for the 15% threshold, for instance. The representative julian day is used as a control variable in the model specification to adjust for the time of year at which the data was collected.

DATA <- read.csv("./OUTPUT/FINAL_DATASET.csv")
# distribution of CHL-a by SIC threshold
ggplot(DATA, aes(x = CHL, y = ..count.., fill = SIC_id)) + 
  geom_histogram(bins=1000) + 
  theme_classic() + 
  labs(x = "CHL-a",
       y = "Freq.",       
       fill = "SIC threshold") + 
  geom_vline(xintercept = 1   , linetype = "dashed") +
  geom_vline(xintercept = 0.75, linetype = "solid") +
  scale_y_continuous(expand = c(0,0)) + 
  scale_x_continuous(expand = c(0,0)) +
  theme(legend.position = c(0.8,0.8))

To test the syncronicity between LRD and CHL1, there are two approaches which can be taken using this dataset. The first would be to examine the association between LRD and CHL-\(\alpha\) activity levels (as proxied through \(\frac{mg}{m^{3}}\) of chlorophyll) using a statistical model. When including LRD as a control variable, the temporal difference between LRD and CHL-\(\alpha\) day (either in days or light-adjusted days/daylight hours) can be used as an explanatory variable in a regression model. The sign, magitude and statistical significance of the coefficient estimate for time between LRD and CHL-\(\alpha\) then provides an indication of the statistical association between time since LRD and CHL-\(\alpha\) levels. Further, time-invariant unobserved heterogeneity between pixels can be adjusted for through the use of a fixed effect term. The result then provides an indication of the assication between time relative to LRD, whilst controlling for fixed factors such as depth, along with julian day due to the Julian day being included in the model specification. Finally, simple transformations can be applied to the model specification to explore the non-linearity of the association. For instance, a simple ‘log-linear’ specification would suggest that temporal distance from LRD is proportionally associated with CHL-\(\alpha\) (See equation XXX below).

The second approach would be to define a threshold for CHL-\(\alpha\), above which that pixel is defined as “blooming”. Research by Blondeau-Patissier et al. [IN-LINE CITATION OF YEAR. SHOULD BE 2014] suggests there to be some discrepency between thresholds in the northern and southern hemispheres, respectively. Further, the authors also identify a lack of consistency in bloom threshold definitions amongst literature within each threshold. Nevertheless, Blondeau-Patissier et al. [IN-LINE CITATION OF YEAR. SHOULD BE 2014] suggest that 1 \(\frac{mg}{m^{3}}\) of CHL-\(\alpha\) should be used, yet reduce their preferred threshold to 0.75 \(\frac{mg}{m^{3}}\) in their analyses, citing the tendancy of SeaWiFS to under-estimate high CHL-\(\alpha\) concentrations. As the globcolour data includes information from SeaWiFS, the threshold used in this analysis is therefore 0.75 \(\frac{mg}{m^{3}}\).

The binary dependant variable approach has the advantage of eliminating the biasing effect which very small CHL-\(\alpha\) (essentially zero) values may have on the coefficient estimate of the linear continuous-variable approach. This is because they make up the vast majority of the observed CHL-\(\alpha\) values. Figure XXX above shows the very high proportion of pixels within the dataset with a corresponding CHL-\(\alpha\) of less than 1 (the dashed line) and less than 0.75 (the solid line). Using the linear regression model on this dataset may result in a biased estimate of the synchronicity between LRD and CHL-\(\alpha\) due to the non-normality of the distribution of CHL-\(\alpha\). The natural logarithm of CHL could be used to “normalise” the distribution, yet this would likely lead to a loss of meaning in the interpretations of the model parameters. On the other hand, a logistic model can be used to capture the influence of time before or since LRD on probability of bloom occuring at that point in time, whilst making many of the same adjustments for fixed effects, individual pixel characteristcs and so on. Finally, the distribution of time between LRD and proportion blooming can also be visually represented in an informative way, which may reveal any important patterns to recognise.

For this investigation, the binary dependant variable approach is preferred. This avoids the issue of very small CHL-\(\alpha\) values biasing the estimates, and provides the most informative statistics on the syncronicity between LRD and CHL-\(\alpha\)

#define in-bloom as 0.75 mg/m^3
DATA$IN_BLOOM <- ifelse(DATA$CHL >= 0.75, 1, 0)
#provide alternative definition for sensitivity analysis
DATA$IN_BLOOM_ALT <- ifelse(DATA$CHL >= 1, 1, 0)

Statistical methodology

One approach to explore the association between LRD and CHL-\(\alpha\) activity quantitively is to model chl-\(\alpha\) levels (as proxied through \(\frac{mg}{m^{3}}\) of chlorophyll), using a linear model. When including LRD as a control variable, the temporal difference between LRD and CHL-\(\alpha\) day (either in days or light-adjusted days/daylight hours) can be used as an explanatory variable in a regression model. The sign, magitude and statistical significance of the coefficient estimate for time between LRD and CHL-\(\alpha\) then provides an indication of the statistical association between time since LRD and CHL-\(\alpha\) levels. Further, time-invariant unobserved heterogeneity between pixels can be adjusted for through the use of a fixed effect term. The result then provides an indication of the assication between time relative to LRD, whilst controlling for fixed factors such as depth, along with julian day due to the Julian day being included in the model specification.

The second approach would be to define a threshold for CHL-\(\alpha\), above which that pixel is defined as “in bloom”. Research by Blondeau-Patissier et al. [IN-LINE CITATION OF YEAR. SHOULD BE 2014] suggests there to be some discrepency between thresholds in the northern and southern hemispheres, respectively. Further, the authors also identify a lack of consistency in bloom threshold definitions amongst literature within each threshold. Nevertheless, Blondeau-Patissier et al. [IN-LINE CITATION OF YEAR. SHOULD BE 2014] suggest that 1 \(\frac{mg}{m^{3}}\) of CHL-\(\alpha\) should be used, yet reduce their preferred threshold to 0.75 \(\frac{mg}{m^{3}}\) in their analyses, citing the tendancy of SeaWiFS to under-estimate high CHL-\(\alpha\) concentrations. As the globcolour data includes information from SeaWiFS, the threshold used in this analysis was consequently 0.75 \(\frac{mg}{m^{3}}\).

The binary dependant variable approach has the advantage of eliminating the biasing effect which very small CHL-\(\alpha\) (essentially zero) values may have on the coefficient estimate of the linear continuous-variable approach. Small values make up the vast majority of the observed CHL-\(\alpha\) data. Figure XXX - the distribution of chl-a in the data below shows the very high proportion of pixels a corresponding CHL-\(\alpha\) of less than 1 (the dashed line) and less than 0.75 (the solid line). Using a linear model to describe this dataset is likely to be biased, due to the non-normality of the distribution of CHL-\(\alpha\). The natural logarithm of CHL could be used to normalise the distribution, yet this would likely lead to a loss of meaning in the results. On the other hand, a simple logistic model can be used to capture the influence of light-adjusted-time relative to LRD on probability of bloom, whilst making the same adjustments for region and year [REF, a book - Dobson, A. J. (1990) An Introduction to Generalized Linear Models. London: Chapman and Hall.]. Finally, the distribution of time between LRD and proportion blooming can also be visually represented in an informative way, which may reveal any important patterns to recognise. For this investigation, the binary dependant variable approach was preferred. This avoided the issue of very small CHL-\(\alpha\) values biasing the estimates, and provided the most informative statistics on the syncronicity between LRD and CHL-\(\alpha\).

In the below model specification, BLOOM represents whether the pixel is in bloom (See above); SIC thresh. is Snow/Ice concentration threshold; \(\alpha\) is a constant term (Conditional mean); \(\beta\) is a linear regression coefficient; \(\epsilon\) is an error term, such that \(\epsilon \sim N(0,\sigma)\), where \(sigma\) is standard deviation; \(\phi_{pjy} = (chl_{jy} - LRD_{py})\times DL_{pj}\), where \(DL_{pj}\) is calculated in the sections below. Consequently, this model estimates whether or not a pixel is ‘in bloom’ using linear parameters based on last retreat day, first advance day, time relative to last retreat day and light availability. This analysis then estimates the synchronicity between light availability and phytoplankton levels whilst adjusting for confounding factors, unobservable environmental-heterogeneities, and even longer-term trends (as captured by the term for year). This model used a logistic link [REF, the R book].

\[\begin{equation} (BLOOM_{prjy} | SIC_{prjy} < SIC thresh.) = \alpha + \beta_{1}LRD_{py} + \beta_{2}\phi_{py} + \beta_{3}FAD_{py} + \beta_{4}r + \beta_{5}y + \epsilon_{pjy} \end{equation}\]

Results

Visual analysis of synchronicity between LRD and blooms

Figure XXX demonstrates the association between JD relative to LRD and the proportion of pixels which are in bloom, by SIC threshold. the solid lines with surrounding bandwidths show the loess smoothing fit, which indicates the general trend and 99% confidence interval of the data. Figure XXX shows the association between light-adjusted time relative to LRD and proportion of pixels in bloom. When measuring time relative to LRD only in terms of daylight-time, the assoication close to LRD remains similar, whilst the association far away from the LRD is very different. The proportion of pixels in bloom continues to rise when neglecting to adjust for the length of those days, whilst the proportion of pixels blooming drops off after 100 light-adjusted days.

x <- DATA

When looking at this on a regional level, the trend is much less consistent. Some regions like Okhotsk have reasonably high bloom proportions year-round, whilst unsurprisingly the central arctic has a reasonably low proportion of pixels with \(chl- \alpha \geq 0.75 mgm^{-3}\). This highlights the importance of controlling for region in the statistical analysis.

x <- DATA
# light adjusted, by region
y <- x %>%
  mutate(CHLJD_APPROX_LADAYS_vs_LRD = round(CHLJD_LADAYS_vs_LRD, 0)) %>%
  group_by(CHLJD_APPROX_LADAYS_vs_LRD, region) %>%
  summarise(perc_in_bloom = mean(IN_BLOOM) * 100)
ggplot(y,
       aes(x = CHLJD_APPROX_LADAYS_vs_LRD,

       ) +

       labs(x = "Days since LRD, light-adjusted",
       y = "% in bloom",
       colour = "Arctic region",
       fill = "Arctic region") +
       theme(legend.position = "bottom")

Generally, the synchronicity between last retreat day and phytoplankton bloom appears to consist of an increase in the approach to and just after the LRD, followed by a large dip and regrowth before finally dropping off for the winter months. There is a particularly large amount of variability in proportions of pixels in blom during the winter months. this may be due to the areas at lower latitude, including the Hudson, and Baffin in juxtoposition to the central Arctic, which appears to have at least some 25 by 25 km extents containing \(chl- \alpha~>~0.75~mgm^{-3}\) for most of, if not the whole year. This could be to do with different, more resilient, species of phytoplankton ocuppying the central Arctic.

The syncronicity can also be shown using a scatter-plot of LRD and ‘first bloom day’, or the first JD in which the pixel had \(chl- \alpha~>~0.75~mgm^{-3}\). Figures XXX to XXX show this via kernel density heatmap. The correlation between LRD and first bloom day seems to be affected by the SIC threshold used, with higher thresholds showing a tighter overall correlation.

The above figures suggest there to be a generally close positive correlation between the LRD of a pixel and the first date upon which that pixel starts to bloom. This seems to be relatively consistent in all regions, with the exception of St. Lawrence, which is at a much lower latitude than the other regions. This region has very early last retreat days, and also low correlation between LRD and first bloom day. The synchronicity between sea ice retreat and phytoplankton bloom appears to be relatively weak in this area, and this is possibly due to the much smaller quantity of pixels in this region which reach SIC of even 15%.

library(reshape2)
regional_cor <- z %>%
  group_by(SIC_id,region) %>%
  dplyr::summarise(correlation = cor(LRD, JD_rep, method='spearman', use='pairwise.complete.obs'))
ggplot(regional_cor, aes(x = region, y = SIC_id, fill = correlation)) +
  geom_tile(color = "white") +
  scale_fill_gradient2(
  low = "white",
  high = "dark green",
  limit = c(-1, 1),
  name = "Pearson\nCorrelation"
  ) +
  labs(x="",y="SIC threshold") +
  theme_classic() +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(
  angle = 45,
  size = 12,
  hjust = 1
  )) +
  geom_text(aes(region, SIC_id, label = round(correlation, 2)),
  color = "black",
  size = 6)

NA

Regression analysis

The regression analysis tables are presented below. All of the regional dummy variables are in reference to Baffin Bay. Pixels with a higher (i.e. later in the year) last retreat day are less likely to be in bloom, which does suggest some synchronicity between ice-adjusted light availability and the probability of bloom. Further, when holding all other factors constant, the earlier in the year the observation is taken, the more likely it is to be in bloom. Interestingly, the Laptev sea in particular has a very high odds ratio of pixels being in bloom at any point in time. When adjusting for day length.
